title: Netanyahu orders ‘powerful’ strikes on Gaza as fragile ceasefire is broken
description: Only a few weeks after the Gaza ceasefire came into effect, Israel has launched fresh strikes on the territory.  Both sides have accused each other of violating the fragile truce.  The strikes followed an order from Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu for "powerful" attacks.  Since those strikes landed, a Hamas-affiliated defence agency has claimed nine people have been killed.  This comes as Hamas has delayed handing over another hostage’s body in response to Israel’s planned strikes.

title: Labor's environmental law reforms put a ‘handbrake’ on investment
description: Liberal Senator Jane Hume says the EPBC Act needs to help not just the environment, but also the economy, which is where "the problem lies”. title: CNN bitterly admit Republican polling has impoved during shutdown
description: CNN has had to admit that the Republicans have gained popularity while breaking down polling data regarding the shutdown.  Chief Data Analyst Harry Enten says the shutdown, which was supposed to hurt the GOP, has actually helped the party's brand.  The polls come amid the federal government shutdown, which began on October 1 and is quickly approaching the one-month mark.  Citing the Generic Congressional Ballot, which shows that the Democrats are less favourable than at the same time during Trump's first term.  Enten goes on to say the Democrats are in their "worst" position in 20 years and that the number is "concerning" for the party.

title: Pat Cummins puts back injury to the test in the nets
description: Australian fast bowler Pat Cummins has been seen putting his back injury to the test in the nets today.  His initial efforts were seen at New South Wales Cricket Central in Sydney’s west today.   Fox Sports News exclusive footage captured the moment the Test captain was seen rolling the arm over.   This move hopes to be a sign for his road to recovery, which will lead him to play some role in the Ashes, after it was revealed Cummins has been dealing with lower lumbar back stress.

title: Inflation spike kills Melbourne Cup rate cut hopes | 7NEWS
description: Australia's inflation rate has risen to 3.2% headline and 3% underlying, marking the first increase in underlying inflation since 2022. Electricity prices have surged 23% over the past 12 months, driving the inflation spike and pushing the underlying rate to the top of the Reserve Bank's 2-3% target band. The Reserve Bank Board is now extremely unlikely to cut the cash rate from its current 3.6% when it meets on Melbourne Cup Day. title: Shark Feeding Frenzy Off Gold Coast's Snapper Rocks | 10 News
description: A spectacular but dangerous natural phenomenon has been caught on camera after a school of bait fish triggered a feeding frenzy at a popular Gold Coast surfing beach yesterday.  Videos posted to social media show a pack of sharks thrashing their fins and tails around in the shallows, attacking a bait ball right on the edge of the sand at Snapper Rocks.  It’s understood the swell has increased and all the bait has moved offshore, with no shark’s sighted since.  The beaches have re-opened, and lifeguards will continue to monitor the waters. title: Liberal Senator crosses the floor and backs David Pocock’s climate bill
description: Liberal Senator Andrew McLachlan has crossed the floor to break ranks with the rest of his party. title: Americans to lose access to food stamps
description: Tens of millions of Americans will lose access to food stamps this weekend.  The looming deadline has sparked furious infighting among lawmakers as the US government shut down enters day 28.  Government officials from 25 US states are suing the Trump administration over the suspension of food stamps, which helped feed more than 42 million Americans.  The Department of Agriculture has a $5 billion fund it could tap into, but it says it’s holding on to the money for its allocated use to provide support in the case of natural disasters as the US heads into the winter storm season.

title: Illegal Afghan migrant goes on stabbing spree murdering one and injuring two others
description: An Afghan migrant has been arrested after stabbing three people and killing one after illegally entering the UK.  Neighbours claimed the suspect stabbed the 49-year-old man walking his dog after he allegedly intervened in the migrant’s separate attack.  The 49-year-old dogwalker, reportedly known in the local community, was killed following the migrant’s attack on a 45-year-old man and a 14-year-old boy.  The 22-year-old Afghan national was tasered and arrested minutes after the stabbing in Uxbridge, London.  According to The Telegraph, the 22-year-old Afghan national arrived in the UK on a lorry in 2020 and was granted asylum and leave until 2022.  The Metropolitan Police described the attack, which occurred on Monday, as a “shocking, senseless act of violence”.

title: Alleged Drug Strikes Kill 14 In Pacific Ocean | 10 News
description: The US military has once again come under scrutiny after launching strikes on four suspected drug-smuggling boats in the eastern Pacific, killing 14 people and leaving one survivor.   Defence Secretary Pete Hegseth said the vessels were linked to “designated terrorist organisations,” but legal experts have questioned the basis for using lethal force outside of war zones.   The Trump administration reportedly approved a classified opinion allowing traffickers to be treated as enemy combatants, a move critics say bypasses judicial oversight and international law.   Mexican authorities have taken charge of rescuing the survivor after being informed by Washington.   It’s the latest in a growing series of strikes raising ethical and legal concerns about the US’s expanding anti-narcotics campaign. title: Hurricane Melissa Weakens To Category 4 After Devastating Jamaica, Heads Towards Cuba | 10 News
description: Hurricane Melissa has weakened to a Category 4 system with sustained winds of 233kph as its eyewall moves off Jamaica’s northern coast, according to the latest National Hurricane Centre update.  The storm made landfall earlier Tuesday in Jamaica’s southwest with winds of up to 297kph, tearing apart homes, toppling trees and powerlines, and triggering widespread flooding and landslides.  Authorities say much of the island remains without power or communication, with entire communities cut off by blocked roads and debris.  Melissa is expected to make a second landfall in eastern Cuba late Tuesday or early Wednesday, still bringing life-threatening storm surge and damaging winds. title: Eight Queensland schools teach students about wrong Ceasar for year 12 exam | ABC NEWS
description: At least eight Queensland high schools have apologised for mixing up the ancient history curriculum and teaching their students about the wrong Ceasar for a year 12 exam.  The prestigious Brisbane State High School warned students they had been taught about Augustus Ceasar rather than Julius Ceasar just days before the test.  The assessment authority said students could be given special consideration, while Queensland Education Minister John-Paul Langbroek launched an investigation into the blunder. title: ‘On her own two feet’: Lidia Thorpe defends threat to burn Parliament House
description: On tonight’s episode of Paul Murray Live, Sky News host Paul Murray analyses Lidia Thorpe, Chris Bowen, US politics and more.

title: ‘I am not done’: Kamala Harris believes ‘history is calling her’ to the presidency
description: Sky News host Paul Murray says Kamala Harris believes “history is still calling her” as she looks to run for presidency again.

title: ‘They argue constantly’: Nigel Farage not concerned about tactical voting
description: Reform UK Leader Nigel Farage is not concerned about tactical voting.  “It might hurt us here and there,” Mr Farage told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “They argue with each other constantly … so to get them to be organised across 600 constituencies.   “I really don’t think that they’ve got the ability to organise this nationwide.”

title: ‘Line after line blacked out’: Chris Bowen’s redacted climate booklet
description: Sky News host Paul Murray refreshes the “important part” of Energy Minister Chris Bowen’s secret briefing.

title: Coalition must hold the government ‘to account’ for their ‘shambles’ energy policy
description: Shadow Energy Minister Dan Tehan details the underlying factors around the Coalition’s net zero policy discussions.  “Already the colleagues are absolutely committed to making sure we can throw all technology at our energy supply,” Mr Tehan told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “Including nuclear, they are very committed.”

title: ‘Destined for great things’: Barron Trump could be president one day
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi stokes predictions Barron Trump could be president one day.  “There's also talk about Donald Trump Jr being the next one up,” Ms Panahi said.   “There are people already having bets on Barron Trump being president one day.  “He’s only 18 but possibly destined for great things.”

title: The next US president could be ‘someone outside of the government’
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada names contenders for the next US president.  “There are young people that are just great at doing battle,” Ms Gada told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “There could even be someone outside of government that we don’t quite think about today that is just one orbit outside."

title: Trump ‘hijacked’ the party: He won’t run for a third term
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada addresses the media’s obsession with US President Donald Trump serving a third term.  “He has completely remade the party. It started as a hijack,” Ms Gada told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “They’re generally following in his footsteps.  “It would be funny, he’d never do this.”

title: ‘Consulting widely’: Coalition continues deliberations on net zero
description: Shadow Energy Minister Dan Tehan presents the Coalition's ongoing deliberations on achieving net zero by 2050.  Mr Tehan emphasised the need for thorough consultations with colleagues and industry before finalising a position.   With 5,000 jobs at Tomago now at risk due to rising energy prices, Tehan urges Prime Minister Anthony Albanese to reassure workers about their future and suggests energy affordability is crucial for sustainability.

title: Mamdani ‘likened to Obama’ for ‘cheap tricks’
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada likens Zohran Mamdani to Obama in his political tactics.  “He doesn’t need to do these cheap tricks,” Ms Gada told Sky News host Rita Panahi.   “He has vast political ambitions.   “Many people have likened him to Obama.  “Very conveniently using one side of his heritage.”

title: ‘Crocodile tears’: Mamdani caught in a lie by internet sleuths
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada calls out New York City mayoral candidate Zohran Mamdani for being caught in a lie.  “Next, it will be his neighbour's pet,” Ms Gada told Sky News host Rita Panahi.   “The internet is incredible at finding these things out.  “He with those crocodile tears … He really is an actor … a very good one.”

title: Democrats ‘deny’ comparing Trump to Hitler despite incriminating videos
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada criticises Democrats lying about making Hitler comparisons to US President Donald Trump despite video evidence.  “I think cause they’re out of options,” Ms Gada told Sky News host Rita Panahi.   “They don’t have the option to rewrite history.  “They only have one option left, which is to deny it.”

title: ‘Election integrity is low’: ‘Problematic’ numbers at California polling stations
description: Sky News Contributor Kosha Gada explains why nobody’s turning out to vote in California.  “There's a big chunk of the California electorate … that just doesn’t feel inspired by any of the options,” Ms Gada told Sky News host Rita Panahi.   “Trust in elections and election integrity is low.  “That is a very problematic thing for democracy.”

title: ‘Frightening scenes’: Dangerous Islamic extremism in the UK
description: Reform UK Leader Nigel Farage is frightened by brazen Islamic extremist groups.  “I hope the left finally wake up, that actually there is something even more dangerous than identity politics that is going on,” Mr Farage told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “I thought the scenes that I witnessed … were simply the most frightening scenes that I have ever, ever seen.  “This is why we have to be very, very careful about who we, both in this and your country, let in.

Gavin Newsom consistently polls at the top of the potential nominees, and it’s interesting,” she said.  “Over the last couple of months, (he’s been) using social media, he’s tried to rebrand himself as dark woke take on Trump, use the memes that the Trump administration uses, and just use it against them, and he’s been remarkably successful.  “I think he’s probably one of the more threatening candidates that could potentially be in the (presidential) race.”

title: Donald Trump touts strong JD Vance & Marco Rubio 2028 presidential ticket
description: US President Donald Trump has labelled a JD Vance and Marco Rubio 2028 presidential ticket “unstoppable” despite not saying he would not seek a third term.  While speaking to reporters on Air Force One, Trump declined to say he would not seek a third term but pointed to several candidates who could replace him.  Trump named the US Vice President Vance and Secretary of State Rubio to continue to hold the White House following the 2028 election.  “Well, we have great people. Well, I don’t have to get into that, but we have one of them standing right here. We have JD [Vance], obviously. The vice president is great,” Trump said.  “Marco [Rubio] is great. I’m not sure if anybody would run against us. I think if they have a form to group it would be unstoppable, I do. I really believe that.”

This follows incumbent Mayor Eric Adams endorsing his once bitter rival Andrew Cuomo in an attempt to beat Mamdani.  New York mayoral candidate Zohran Mamdani vowed to "take the city back" at a rally as the race enters its final stretch.  Cuomo, Mamdani and Republican nominee Curtis Sliwa all traded barbs in the final NYC mayoral debate.

title: King Charles heckled over brother Prince Andrew | ABC NEWS
description: King Charles was heckled by a protester on Monday over his brother Prince Andrew's ties to the late sex offender Jeffrey Epstein. The king was greeting royal fans during a cathedral visit in Britain.  "How long have you known about Andrew and Epstein?," the man could be heard shouting outside Lichfield Cathedral in northwest England, close to Birmingham.  Although Prince Andrew, 65, said this month that he would give up using his title of Duke of York after years of scrutiny over his behaviour and connections to Epstein, questions about him — and what the royals knew of events — have intensified since.  The contents of a posthumous memoir by Virginia Giuffre, who accused the prince of sexually abusing her as a teenager, have triggered renewed backlash over the issue this month.  Andrew has always denied Giuffre's account. In 2022, he made an undisclosed payment to settle a lawsuit brought in the US by Giuffre, who died by suicide in April.  British police are looking into media reports that in 2011 Andrew had asked one of his police officers to dig up dirt on Giuffre.  The protester could also be heard saying: "Have you asked the police to cover up for Andrew? ... Should the MPs (members of parliament) be allowed to debate the royals in the House of Commons?"  The monarch ignored the protester and carried on engaging with other members of the public.  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Donald Trump says he 'would love' third term | ABC NEWS
description: US President Donald Trump ruled out running for the vice presidency in the 2028 election, an approach some of his supporters have floated to allow the Republican president to serve an additional term in office. The remarks were Trump's latest on the subject, which he has teased in public remarks and with "Trump 2028" hats he hands out at the White House. No one may be elected to the US presidency a third time, according to the 22nd Amendment of the US Constitution. Some have suggested that one way around this prohibition would be for Trump to stand as vice president, while another candidate stood for president and resigned, letting Trump again assume the presidency. Opponents have disputed whether this would be legal. Referring to Vice President JD Vance and Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Trump also said they were "great people" who could run for the office. title: Trump Again Refuses To Rule Out Third Presidential Run | 10 News
description: US President Donald Trump has once again refused to categorically rule out attempting to run for a third presidential term, further stoking rising fears he may try to subvert the US constitution.  The constitution's 22nd amendment prevents anyone from being elected to the office of president more than twice. However, this hasn't stopped rampant speculation that Trump will mount a move to either remain in office in 2028, or find a legal workaround to permit a third tilt at the presidency.  Speaking aboard Air Force One, Trump was asked point-blank if he would rule out a third run. "Am I ruling it out? You tell me," he responded. Trump did, however, address one popularly held theory that he could run as Vice President behind JD Vance, with Vance immediately stepping down after winning an election. Despite that too being constitutionally forbidden, Trump said he would not do it because "it's too cute." title: ‘Threat of China’: Albanese meets with Chinese Premier Li
description: Sky News host Sharri Markson discusses the “threat of China” as Prime Minister Anthony Albanese meets with Chinese Premier Li Qiang.  “The threat of China’s aggressive conduct is the underlying concern … two US aircraft have crashed over the South China Sea. This is alarming and we await more details from the United States about the cause,” Ms Markson said.  “Prime Minister Anthony Albanese met with Chinese Premier Li Qiang today for their bilateral, it was their seventh meeting and it came just a week after a dangerous incident for Australian pilots over the South China Sea.”

title: ‘Fighting a war’: Iran allegedly orchestrates worldwide antisemitic attacks

description: Treasurer Jim Chalmers has hit out at the “divided” Coalition which is currently in “disarray” as he pointed out the difference between himself and Shadow Treasurer Ted O’Brien.  “The difference between the Shadow Treasurer and myself as Treasurer I’m here for the outcomes. I’m here to deliver for the working people of this country,” he said during Question Time on Monday.  “The Shadow Treasurer’s here for a little pat on the head on Sky After Dark or a little tickle on the tummy on Page 13 of The Australian. We are here for the outcomes.  “We are delivering – they are divided, they are divisive, they are in disarray, and that’s the difference.”

title: Putin touts the potential of ‘invincible’ nuclear-capable cruise missile
description: Russian President Vladimir Putin has boasted about the capability of Russia's "invincible" nuclear-capable cruise missile.  The Burevestnik missile, or known by its NATO code-name as "Skyfall", was successfully tested on Sunday, said Putin.  The Russian president appeared in military fatigues to tout the success of his new missile.  During the address, Putin called on his top generals to begin preparing missiles for potential use.  "We need to determine the possible uses and begin preparing the infrastructure for deploying these weapons to our armed forces", Putin said.  Previously, Putin said the weapon is capable of bypassing missile defence systems and has an almost infinite range.  Moscow has boasted of the missile's capability, but it remains unclear if the Burevestnik missile can do what Putin says it can.

title: Clare O’Neil calls out the Greens for playing a ‘disgraceful act of politics’
description: Housing Minister Clare O’Neil has called out the Greens during Question Time over the party’s “disgraceful act of politics” over the last three years.  “The Greens played a disgraceful act of politics over the last three years,” she said.  “They came into this parliament day after day after day, saying that they were advocating for people who need housing support and, at the same time, doing everything they could to work with the Liberal Party to block housing.  “I hope that in this new term of parliament, the Greens have got the opportunity to turn over a new leaf.”

title: CBS anchor goes off on Hakeem Jeffries after he claimed the midterms will be ‘rigged elections’
description: CBS anchor Margaret Brennan has called out House Minority Leader Hakeem Jeffries over his claims about the upcoming midterm elections.  During an interview on CBS’s ‘Face the Nation', Brennan pressed Jeffries for hypocritically suggesting the midterms could be “rigged elections”.  In the past, the minority leader asserted there were “no election deniers” in the Democratic Party.  “Democrats were appalled when President Trump used language like that,” Brennan said.  “How do you justify using that now? Doesn’t that undermine faith for voters you need to show up?”  Jeffries quickly went on the defensive, claiming his comments were taken out of context, referring to Republicans’ gerrymandering of congressional maps.

title: ‘He’s always ready for fun’: Trump was ‘really going for it’ as he dances on Malaysian tarmac
description: Sky News host Danica De Giorgio says US President Donald Trump is the “only one with the moves” as he was seen dancing in Malaysia as he arrived.  “I thought it was quite a wonderful welcome,” Ms De Giorgio said.  “It’s got elements of YMCA, but the hips were really going for it.  “Good on him, he gets off the plane and he’s always ready for fun.”

title: Unhinged Democrat launches call to demolish Trump's White House ballroom
description: Democrats are continuing to be in complete meltdown over Donald Trump’s multi-million dollar revamp of the White House ballroom.  California Representative Eric Swalwell has urged the next Democratic presidential nominee to demolish President Trump's White House ballroom if they were to win in 2028.  "Don’t even think of seeking the Democratic nomination for president unless you pledge to take a wrecking ball to the Trump Ballroom on DAY ONE," Mr Swalwell posted to X.  White House press secretary Karoline Leavitt urged Americans to "trust the process" and vowed the new ballroom will be "magnificent."  Prominent Democrats have chimed in unsubstantiated claims that the ballroom overhaul is President Trump’s “main priority”.

title: Albanese and Trump’s warm rapport was ‘evident’ for all to see in recent meeting
description: Acting Prime Minister Richard Marles has reacted to the recent meeting between United States President Donald Trump and Prime Minister Anthony Albanese.   “The meeting was warm, it was engaging, it was constructive,” Mr Marles said during Question Time on Monday.   “They signed a landmark critical minerals framework agreement.  “[Albanese] very much enjoyed the time that he spent with President Trump; there was a connection and a warm rapport which was evident for all to see, and that is a very good thing.”

title: Hamas withholding deceased hostages is a ‘delaying tactic’ to ‘psychologically damage’ Jews
description: AIJAC Executive Manager Joel Burnie says Israelis feel “bittersweet” with the return of the hostages, as Hamas is still withholding the bodies of deceased hostages.   “Whilst the country is in the process of healing and it is overjoyed with the return of the living hostages, there are some double-digit number of deceased hostages that are still yet to be released,” Mr Burnie said.   “Hamas had given their promises that there would be and there haven’t been.   “This is a Hamas delaying tactic to again psychologically damage the Israeli citizenry in delaying the release of these hostages.  “There are still a number of families where their loved ones, their bones and bodies, are still somewhere deep underground in Gaza waiting for a proper burial and some proper closure.”

title: This is what a modern day gold rush looks like #abcnewsshorts
description: Thousands of people have been queueing up at gold selling sites such as ABC Bullion and the Perth Mint to buy gold over the past month. Some people have queued up for hours in Sydney's heat to buy the precious metal, which recently passed $US4,300 an ounce. Analysts say it's related to so-called safe haven demand, as people are worried about global tensions and the economy. Gold holds its value, or at least it has done in the past, so it's seen as a bit of a bunker in case a financial meltdown hits.  #ABCBusiness  Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Israeli satire program brutally mocks Gaza Greta's flotilla
description: Greta Thunberg has been utterly humiliated as part of an Israeli satire show making fun of her flotilla to Gaza.  Israel’s number one satire program, Eretz Nehederet, mocked the Swedish activist in its latest English-language skit.  The parody follows Thunberg and other anti-Israel activists sailing to Gaza’s shores in the distance but then finding out about the ceasefire between Israel and Hamas.  Thunberg’s character reacts angrily to the news of the ceasefire because she can no longer protest about it.  This comes as the International Court of Justice ordered Israel to permit UN aid efforts in Gaza.

title: John Fetterman savagely breaks with Democrats over Government shutdown
description: Democratic Senator John Fetterman has broken ranks with the Democrats to vote with Republicans to avoid prolonging a government shutdown.  The US government shutdown has now reached one of the longest in US history as Democrats and Republicans battle over healthcare funding.  Fetterman and a few other lawmakers broke ranks with the party, voting with Republicans to reopen the government.  The Senate failed to advance a Republican bill to pay federal workers during the shutdown, falling short of 60 votes with a 54-46 vote.  Three Democrats, including John Fetterman, voted with the Republican Party.

Owner Beck Smith runs her property largely alone and credits her working dogs with helping her through tough times, including recovery from catastrophic flooding earlier this year. title: ‘Uncomfortable situation’: Australia braces for a ‘material upside shock’ to inflation

title: Donald Trump’s deadline for Hamas to return hostage bodies looms
description: The deadline looms after US President Donald Trump gave Hamas 48 hours to return the deceased hostages.  Trump took to his social media platform, Truth Social, to issue an ultimatum to Hamas over the return of the hostages on Saturday.  The president has denied on more than one occasion that the US will put boots on the ground in Gaza, but Trump says there are military forces in the region who could intervene.  Trump's comments come as 13 hostages remain in Gaza, following the recent release of the living hostages.  Following the signing of the peace plan, reports arose of Hamas killing people in Gaza. Sky News host Chris Kenny comments on a video released by Israel showing violence by Hamas.  For more Hamas' violent actions following the signing of the peace agreement, Sky News host Sharri Markson was joined by Israeli News Anchor Lital Shemesh.  WARNING: Distressing content.

title: Egyptian excavators enter Gaza to find Israeli hostage bodies | ABC NEWS
description: Israeli authorities have allowed an Egyptian excavation team to enter Gaza through the Rafah border crossing to find the bodies of deceased Israeli hostages.  The team will work with Red Cross to locate the remains under rubble and will operate inside Israel’s yellow line. Israel is accusing Hamas of deliberately delaying the return of hostage bodies. The Israel-Hamas ceasefire appears to be holding despite several Israeli strikes on targets deemed to be threats to Israeli security. Meanwhile, Israeli media is describing US officials’ consistent visits to Israel as ‘Bibi-sitting’, suggesting Washington is actively deterring the Israeli Prime Minister from reigniting the Gaza war. title: US government shutdown affecting air travel amid staffing shortages
description: The near-month-long government shutdown in the United States is affecting air travel.  Safety concerns are rising after airports across the country report major staffing shortages.  This comes as thousands of flights have been delayed as airports across the country deal with staffing shortages.  TSA agents and air traffic controllers are still required to show up to work due to being an essential employee, despite not getting paid, due to the government shutdown.  However, many employees are having to call out sick because they say they can’t afford to pay for things such as gas and childcare costs.  Since the shutdown began at the start of October, more than 250 Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) facilities have reported staffing problems.

title: Destructive Storms Lash Brisbane And Parts Of South East Queensland | 10 News
description: More than 25,000 households remain without power after destructive storms battered Brisbane and other parts of south east Queensland with giant hail, damaging winds, rain and lightning.  Hundreds of videos posted to social media show the extent of the damage across the region with outdoor furniture seen flying off balconies including a bbq, along with golf ball-sized hail pounding down in backyards and a tree on fire after being struck by lightning. title: Trump Slams UN, Accepts Nobel Peace Prize Nomination After Thai-Cambodia Peace Deal | 10 News
description: US President Donald Trump has claimed a peace accord between Thailand and Cambodia, while taking petty shots at the United Nations over the now-infamous teleprompter and escalator incidents.  Speaking in Kuala Lumpur following the signing of a ceasefire agreement between the two warring nations, Trump brought up how the UN "should be doing this" and that "they turned off my teleprompter when I made a speech." Trump also once again claimed the United States was the "hottest country anywhere in the world," and that ending wars was something "much more serious than a hobby" for him.  Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Manet glowingly thanked President Trump for his role in brokering the ceasefire accord - which also came with the announcement of a rare earth minerals deal between the US and Thailand - confirming he had formally nominated Trump for the Nobel Peace Prize.
